06171nam a22010935i 9780691214931DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020032356  a9780691214931  a(DE-B1597)572671  a(OCoLC)1178869545  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHM641 4aHM641b.M677 2021 7aBUS0690002bisacsh04a303.382231 aMorson, Gary Saul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMinds Wide Shut :bHow the New Fundamentalisms Divide Us /cGary Saul Morson, Morton Schapiro. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface: Toward Dialogue -- tMinds Wide Shut -- t1 Fundamentalism Writ Large -- t2 Fundamentalism and Its Alternatives: From Fanaticism to Dialogue -- t3 Divided We Stand: The Politics of Hate -- t4 Price and Prejudice: Economics and the Quest for Truth -- t5 Searching for Eternal Truths: Religion and Its Discontents -- t6 Literature: How to Ruin It and Why You Shouldn’t -- t7 A Path Forward -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA timely exploration of intellectual dogmatism in politics, economics, religion, and literature—and what can be done to fight itPolarization may be pushing democracy to the breaking point. But few have explored the larger, interconnected forces that have set the stage for this crisis: namely, a rise in styles of thought, across a range of fields, that literary scholar Gary Saul Morson and economist Morton Schapiro call “fundamentalist.” In Minds Wide Shut, Morson and Schapiro examine how rigid adherence to ideological thinking has altered politics, economics, religion, and literature in ways that are mutually reinforcing and antithetical to the open-mindedness and readiness to compromise that animate democracy. In response, they propose alternatives that would again make serious dialogue possible.Fundamentalist thinking, Morson and Schapiro argue, is not limited to any one camp. It flourishes across the political spectrum, giving rise to dueling monologues of shouting and abuse between those who are certain that they can’t be wrong, that truth and justice are all on their side, and that there is nothing to learn from their opponents, who must be evil or deluded. But things don’t have to be this way. Drawing on a wide range of thinkers and writers from across the humanities and social sciences, Morson and Schapiro show how we might begin to return to meaningful dialogue through case-based reasoning, objective analyses, lessons drawn from literature, and more.The result is a powerful invitation to leave behind simplification, rigidity, and extremism—and to move toward a future of greater open-mindedness, moderation, and, perhaps, even wisdom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aExtremists. 0aIdeology and literature. 0aIdeology. 0aPolarization (Social sciences) 0aPolarization (Social sciences). 0aReligious fundamentalism. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aAdam Smith.  aBible.  aChekhov.  aEnemies.  aclimate change.  adeath of dialogue.  aempathy.  aextremism.  ahumanism and economics.  ahumanistic economics.  aideologues.  amarket fundamentalism.  apolitical polarization.  aproblem of certainty.  apseudoscience.  aradical skepticism.  asilo.  athreats to democracy.  atyranny of experts.  avalue of dialogue.1 aSchapiro, Morton, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2021 Englishz978311075404908iTitle is part of eBook package